                    OVERVIEW OF MOORE/CAD IC DESIGN SYSTEM

Schematic entry:

Two levels of binary encoded net formats are avalible. ".net" provides
a herarchal format, and ".sim" provides the flat net. The formats are
designed to represent a network of N and P mosfets, resistors, and
single terminal capacitors. The length and width of the mosfets is included.
This information provides the basis for switch level and circuit level
simulation (limited to the case of digital CMOS), and layout systems
interface.
We provide an ascii text format language which contains these elements,
and provides cell, vector constructs and other convieninces. Alternately,
the output of a schematic editor (or even a grapics editor) can be converted
to the binary transport format at any given level.
When the convertion to flat net is made, library cell processing is done.
The input format may include essentail analog components, or all components
including parasitics.

Simulation:

Two distinct levels of simulation can be performed, switch and circuit. Each
level consists of both a software and hardware module whose function is
almost directly identical.
Switch level simulation strips off the length and width information, the
capacitors, and emulates resistors with weak fets tied "on". It proofs the
logical function of the circuit, at very high speed.
Circuit level simulation uses all given information, along with provided
process parameters. It gives a full analog simulation, and good accuracy,
with speeds typically only 100 times slower than the switch simulator.
Using the hardware accelerator, this makes possible the delay calculation
phase of an IC project do be done with a SPICE like simulator, even for
a large IC. The parisitic inclusion level can be ramped up as the project
reaches term, resulting in increasing levels of accuracy.

Layout:

We provide a symbolic system known as "microcells", with a software and
hardware module to generate them. Using a limited geometery system, a cell
specified in the ".net" format can be automatically laid out in resonable
time. To do this, it strips all analog components off the cell, then
accepts a "skeletal" layout (which contains manual sections), then generates
a layout. A "real" net consisting of the cell with all proper parisitics
can be generated, and back fed into the simulations.
